#   SUBS: submodule-recursion tickets

Audit of `be`'s submodule recursion across all verbs (2026-06-05).  Model
and spec in [Submodules].  Recursion is **default-on for every source type**
(git/ssh included); `--sub` is a dead no-op, `--nosub` is the only opt-out.
HEAD, GET (checkout/clone/force/prune), and POST topology (post-order,
synthetic dot-branch `?/<sub>/.<parent>/<branch>`, gitlink bumps,
detached-refuse) all work.  SUBS-001..012, 016, 017, 018 landed; the gaps
below are the deltas that remain.

| Ticket | Sev | Verb | One-line |
|--------|-----|------|----------|
| [SUBS-019] | HIGH | post | `be post` records the git **empty sha** `e69de29b` as the parent gitlink when the sub is dirty after a `be patch` re-mount (never commits the sub first) → poisoned parent commit, later `be get`/`be patch` dies `not a commit`. Blocked MEM-021's land. Worker owns `~/todo/MEM-021`; repro-first in `test/`. |
| [SUBS-013] | LOW | put | full `git submodule add` parity: stage a new `160000` gitlink + `.gitmodules` from `be put` — needs a chosen URL source + pin grammar (escalated from SUBS-009) |
| [SUBS-014] | LOW | put | misleading "does not exist — skipped" PUTNONE fires for ANY plain untracked dir named without a trailing slash (not sub-specific); wants a "did you mean `dir/`?" hint |
| [SUBS-015] | LOW | blob | `blob:<path>` WITHOUT `?ref` returns KEEPNONE even in the parent (pre-existing, not sub-related) |

